core.name: Party Classification
core.description: Parties can be classified based on ownership, liability, industry classification, minority classification, size classification, income classification, or specialization. For example, you might use the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) or the Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) to categorize parties. In the healthcare sector, you might classify parties based on specialities, such as pediatrics or ophthalmology.

core.name: Party Employment
core.description: Employment details of a party comprise the name of employer, line of business, location, etc.

core.name: Party Group
core.description: Party group is the category to which the party belongs. A group is an informal structure of persons or organizations, such as a household, a special interest or advocacy group, or a project group. Individual parties can be grouped if they are affiliated together and you want to treat them as a separate entity. A party can belong to one or more groups depending on the rules defined for categorizing the parties. For example, a household is a set of persons (parties) who are extended members of the same family, and who can be treated as a unit for certain purposes, such as marketing.

core.name: Party Status
core.description: The status of a party can be registered, approved, active, or inactive.

core.name: Party Opt In Information
core.description: Parties specify whether an organization can contact them and what kind of contact is acceptable. For example, a party might allow marketers to send information, messages, or merchandise about products and services to the party or might restrict marketers from any contact with the party.

core.name: Party Phone Communication
core.description: Phone numbers can be landline, mobile, or fax. Phone numbers might be bound to the postal address of the party. The availability of the phone number, effective date, and validity provide additional information for phone communication with the party.

core.name: Party Lifestyle
core.description: Lifestyle details give additional information about the party applicable to a person, such as behavior and interests. Lifestyle information includes travel style, hobbies, and entertainment preferences.

core.name: Party Alternate Name
core.description: An organization or a person might use different names, such as legal name, professional name, alias, doing business as, and maiden name. An alternative name might be active during a particular time.

core.name: Party Communication Preference
core.description: Communication with a party must adhere to the communication preference of the party. You can store how, when, and where a party prefers to receive communication, information, or messages. You can add the communication preference on all communication channels, such as physical address, email address, phone, and social media.

core.name: Postal Address Enrichment Status
core.description: Postal addresses can be standardized and enriched with data, such as county code, postal code, and locality identifiers. You can have country-specific address enrichments to improve the address quality and usability. When you enrich postal addresses, the enrichment service might return status codes along with the address output.

core.name: Party Education

core.name: Party Demography

core.name: Party Availability
core.description: Contact points for a party include phone number, electronic address, and postal address. The availability of the party at any given contact point aids the communication with the party.

core.name: Party Documents
core.description: A party in the context of the role submits certain documents, such as a bank statement, a salary slip, qualification certificates, proof of age, and proof of residence.

core.name: Party Alternate Identifier
core.description: Alternate identifiers are known identifiers that uniquely identify a party. For an organization, examples of alternate identifiers are tax numbers, D-U-N-S number, or National Provider Identifier (NPI) numbers for healthcare providers. For a person, examples of alternate identifiers are Social Security number, driver's license number, or passport number.

core.name: Party Electronic Address
core.description: Electronic addresses are email addresses or web addresses.

core.name: Party Key Executive
core.description: If the party is an organization, the key executives are important people in the organization. Key executives include CEO and CFO.

core.name: Party Segment
core.description: Segmentation is the categorization of the party based on different factors, such as age, gender, income, spending patterns, and location. You can use the categorization data to target the marketing efforts and provide special pricing or special terms to the parties.
